Certainly! I'll create a page similar to the one shown in the image. The image displays a simple "Hello World!" page with a blue heading and a green subheading. Let's implement this in our React application.



Now, let's update the `Index.tsx` file to create the page similar to the one in the image:


import React from 'react';

const Index = () => {
  return (
    <div className="min-h-screen flex flex-col items-center justify-center bg-white">
      <h1 className="text-6xl font-bold mb-4 text-hello-blue">Hello World!</h1>
      <p className="text-xl text-welcome-green">Welcome to my first web page!</p>

I understand the issue. The error is occurring because the `border-border` class is not defined in your Tailwind CSS configuration. Let's fix this by updating the necessary files.



Now, let's update the `index.css` file to include the necessary CSS variables:


